From the twitpic page of DeanOut

[Burning
tires](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WTQB1Dhy2i8&feature=player_embedded) and
grenade blasts have rocked the Red Shirt protest zone. Here is a citizen video
footage

Eyewitness accounts have been uploaded on the web. For example, [Nick
Nostitz](http://asiapacific.anu.edu.au/newmandala/2010/05/16/nick-nostitz-in-
the-killing-zone/) was inside the “killing zone”.
_[Vaitor](http://www.vaitor.com/?p=1606)_ and _[Riding out the
Economy](http://www.ridingouttheeconomy.com/?p=2297)_ also posted their
observations of the clashes. A
[Facebook](http://www.prachatai.org/english/node/1807) user posted this entry,
“What should I feel when I wake up one day with the dead bodies of Thais in
front of my house?” But netizens are questioning the authenticity of this
expose. Are they [fake dead
bodies](http://www.oknation.net/blog/canthai/2010/05/15/entry-5)?

[![](https://globalvoicesonline.org/wp-content/uploads/2010/05/Bangkok-
warzone-300x225.jpg)](http://tweetphoto.com/22493591)

Tweetphoto from aleithead

Kishen, writing for _New Mandala_ , is worried about the social, political and
economic
[impact](http://asiapacific.anu.edu.au/newmandala/2010/05/15/thailands-
sideshow-is-over/?utm_source=twitterfeed&utm_medium=twitter) of the ongoing
clashes

> But everyone is fighting it out without considering the enormous economic
> and political ramification to Thailand as a whole. Thailand’s economic
> growth for the year will be badly hampered if matters prolong. As it is this
> year’s drought will have a telling impact on country’s exports of agri-
> produce.
>
> As such, the wounds inflicted on Thailand’s psyche and image in the next few
> days could have a lasting impact on Thailand future growth as a nation.
> That’s a greater wound that all the grenades, .308 bullets and armoured
> personal carriers can inflict on the Thai people

Another citizen video of the
[clashes](http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Sji8B0L7RY4&feature=player_embedded)
between soldiers and protesters

_News in Bangkok_ speculates that
[journalists](http://news.inbangkok.org/?p=2359&utm_source=feedburner&utm_medium=feed&utm_campaign=Feed:+inbangkok/ZhJY+\(News+in+Bangkok\))
were deliberately targeted by snipers

> I suspected that the shooting of the reporters seemed intentional. I
> suspected that the intentional targeting of reporters were to prevent them
> from filming the carnage. I now feel more confident that I am right.

